-- PRESS DIGEST-Hong Kong - July 15
-- By Clare Jim
-- Mon Jul 14, 2014 09:09PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, July 15 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Tuesday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST -- Six rounds of mortgage tightening by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority since 2009 have reduced lending but not reined in prices, latest figures show. [ID:nNrm5jMyKp]-- Hong Kong's political reform process takes its first step on Tuesday with the unveiling of its chief Leung Chun-ying's report to Beijing on the electoral overhaul needed to achieve universal suffrage for the chief executive election in 2017. [ID:nNrm7NnM9j] -- The Financial Services Development Council will study how Hong Kong professionals and the market could better serve mainland companies expanding into international markets. [nNrm1kVsQ9]  THE STANDARD -- Hong Kong Monetary Authority Chief Executive Norman Chan said in his blog that property curbs can be relaxed once the market's downward cycle is confirmed, but he has yet to see when it would happen. (http://bit.ly/1tKlrq6) -- Hong Kong Exchanges and Clearing <0388.HK> Chief Executive Charles Li said contingency plans are in place for Occupy Central. He also said a drill for the Shanghai-Hong Kong Stock Connect programme will be held in September. (http://bit.ly/1qBAgFK)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Chinese investment bank China International Capital Corp (CICC) plans to list in Hong Kong and wants to start a beauty parade for its initial public offering in the coming weeks.   HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES -- Seventy percent of the 178 residential projects currently under construction are small to medium-sized apartments, involving 27,600 units. They will be in the market in the next two to three years, easing the demand from first-home buyers.